em is also implemented\nin a multi-robotic testbed for practical evaluation.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 13 Jan 2020 04:26:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-03"}
{"id":"2001.04058","submitter":"Victor Starovoitov","authors":"Victor N. Starovoitov","title":"Boundary value problem for a global in time parabolic equation","comments":"This work was supported by Russian Science Foundation (grant\n  No.~19-11-00069)","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1002/mma.6816","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The aim of this paper is to draw attention to an interesting semilinear\nparabolic equation that arose when describing the chaotic dynamics of a polymer\nmolecule in a liquid. This equation is nonlocal in time and contains a term,\ncalled the interaction potential, that depends on the time-integral of the\nsolution over the entire interval of solving the problem. In fact, one needs to\nknow the \"future\" in order to determine the coefficient in this term, i.e., the\ncausality principle is violated. The existence of a weak solution of the\ninitial boundary value problem is proven. The interaction potential satisfies\nfairly general conditions and can have an arbitrary growth at infinity. The\nuniqueness of this solution is established with restrictions on the length of\nthe considered time interval.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 13 Jan 2020 04:32:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-12-30"}
