{"id":"2001.04125","submitter":"Simon Cox","authors":"S.J. Cox and I.T. Davies","title":"Bubble entrainment by a sphere falling through a horizontal soap foam","comments":"12 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1209/0295-5075/130/14002","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We simulate the quasi-static motion of a spherical particle through a stable,\nhorizontal soap film. The soap film subtends a fixed contact angle, in the\nrange $10-135^\\circ$, where it meets the particle. The tension and pressure\nforces acting on the particle are calculated in two cases: when the film is\nheld within a vertical cylinder, trapping a bubble but otherwise free to move\nvertically, and when the outer rim of the film is held in a fixed circular wire\nframe. Film deformation is greater in the second case, and the duration of the\ninteraction therefore increases, increasing the contact time between particle\nand film. As the soap film returns towards its equilibrium shape following the\npassage of the particle a small bubble is trapped for contact angles below a\nthreshold value of $90^\\circ$. We show that this bubble is larger when the\nparticle is larger and when the contact angle is smaller.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 13 Jan 2020 09:49:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-26"}
